  "text": "Django migration squashing compliance is implemented across several key files in the django/db/migrations module:\n\n**Squash Migration Generator**: The squashmigrations command (django/core/management/commands/squashmigrations.py) is the primary interface for generating squashed migrations. The Command.handle() method (lines 61-253) orchestrates the squashing process by: loading the migration graph, identifying migrations to squash, collecting their operations, optimizing operations, and creating a new Migration subclass with the 'replaces' attribute set to the list of squashed migrations (line 176, 185). The migration is then written to disk using MigrationWriter.\n\n**Replaced-Migrations Tracking**: The replaced-migrations tracking system is managed in django/db/migrations/loader.py through the MigrationLoader class. The self.replacements dictionary (line 293) stores all migrations that replace other migrations. The build_graph() method (line 274) populates this dictionary by scanning disk migrations for those with non-empty replaces attributes (line 297-298). The replace_migration() method (line 235) processes each replacing migration, resolving chains of replacements using _resolve_replaced_migration_keys() (line 224), and determining whether to use the replacement or original migrations based on their application status.\n\n**Dependency Graph Validation**: The MigrationGraph class (django/db/migrations/graph.py) provides critical methods for dependency graph validation after squashing. The remove_replaced_nodes() method (line 125) removes replaced migration nodes from the graph when a replacement is applicable, remapping dependencies to point to the replacement. The remove_replacement_node() method (line 161) performs the inverse operation when a replacement is only partially applied. The validate_consistency() method (line 198) ensures no DummyNode instances remain in the graph—DummyNode (line 46) represents squashed migrations that were removed but are still referenced, indicating an error condition that must be resolved before migration execution.\n\n**Squash Completeness Check**: Completeness is verified through multiple mechanisms. The all_replaced_applied() method in MigrationLoader (line 372) recursively checks whether all replaced migrations have been applied, handling chains of squashed migrations. During build_graph(), consistency is validated (line 313) by calling graph.validate_consistency(). In the executor, MigrationExecutor.check_replacements() (line 294) marks replacement migrations as applied if all their replaced migrations are applied, maintaining consistency when squash migrations are introduced to an existing deployment. The record_migration() method (line 268) ensures that when a squashed migration is applied, all its replaced migrations are properly recorded as applied in the migration recorder.\n\nThe Migration class (django/db/migrations/migration.py, line 42) defines the replaces attribute as a class-level list that tracks which migrations a squashed migration replaces. MigrationWriter (django/db/migrations/writer.py, lines 194-197) serializes this replaces attribute into the migration file template, generating the appropriate Python code in the output migration.\n\nTogether, these components ensure that squashed migrations are properly tracked, dependencies are correctly maintained, and the system remains consistent when transitioning from a set of individual migrations to their squashed equivalent."
}

